NTURY SIENA: THE BYZANTINE TREASURY OF THE HOSPITAL OF SANTA MARIA DELLA SCALA -- t14 VISUAL RELIGIOUS EDUCATION IN LATE MEDIEVAL FLORENCE: ZANOBI PERINI, THE LEGGENDA DI SANTO TOBIA, AND THE MISERICORDIA -- t15 SAINTS AND STATUS IN LATE MEDIEVAL AND EARLY RENAISSANCE FLORENCE -- tSELECT BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tPUBLICATIONS BY JOANNA CANNON -- tINDEX -- tTABULA GRATULATORIA -- tPlate0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJoanna Cannon's scholarship and teaching have helped shape the historical study of thirteenth- and fourteenth-century Italian art; this essay collection by her former students is a tribute to her work.The essays collected here form a tribute to Joanna Cannon, whose scholarship and teaching have done so much to shape the historical study of thirteenth- and fourteenth-century Italian art. Her teaching lies at the heart of this book, as its chapters are all written by those who gained their doctorates under her supervision. The reach of her interests and expertise is also reflected in its range of subjects. The book is unified by its concentration on Italian art, history, and material culture, spanning the thirteenth to the fifteenth centuries; but within that scope the individual essays focus on an impressive variety of subjects, across many media, including panel painting, wall painting, architecture, sculpture, metalwork, manuscripts, and gilded glass. Ranging across Italy, from Bologna, to Siena, to Assisi, to Florence, they address key themes in the field, such as artistic patronage, sainthood and sanctity, the visual culture of the mendicant orders, devotional practice, and civic religion. Some essays bring fresh approaches to familiar material (Ambrogio Lorenzetti's Saint Nicholas panels, the frescoes in Siena's Palazzo Pubblico, Simone Martini's Holy Family), while others illuminate objects and images that are less well known (the central panel of the Santa Chiara triptych in Trieste, and the statue of Saint Francis in San Francesco in Siena). As a collection they combine to make an important contribution to the study of Early Italian art, seeking thereby to echo the extraordinary contribution of Joanna Cannon's own work to that field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt, Italiany13th century. 0aArt, Italiany14th century. 0aArt, Italiany15th century. 4aArt & Architecture. 4aMedieval History. 7aART / European.2bisacsh  aAmbrogio Lorenzetti.  aArtistic Patronage.  aGilded Glass.  aManuscripts.  aMendicant Orders.  aMetalwork.  aPanel Painting.  aSaint Francis in San Francesco.  aSanta Chiara triptych.  aSculpture.  aSiena's Palazzo Pubblico.  aSimone Martini.  aWall Painting.1 aBotana, Federico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrilliant, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, James Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Donal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Donal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCornelison, Sally J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Glyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Wesselow, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerevini, Stefania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeene, Bryan C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRenner, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, Jessica N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v